# Slide — Industry Practices for SCCM Management Models

**Configuration Manager supports both servers and workstations**, but many large enterprises separate them for governance and operational reasons.

Common enterprise models include:

**Model 1 – Separate SCCM Environments (Most Common)**

* SCCM instance dedicated to **Workstations (EUC managed)**
* SCCM instance dedicated to **Servers (Server Engineering managed)**

**Model 2 – Mixed Tooling Strategy**

* Workstations managed by **SCCM / Intune**
* Servers managed by **automation platforms** (Ansible, Puppet, Chef, Satellite)

**Model 3 – Modern Management Transition**

* Workstations migrating to **Intune / cloud management**
* Servers remaining under **Configuration Manager**

Maintaining separation allows organizations to align **management tools with operational responsibilities and risk tolerance**.

---

# Slide — Operational Differences Between Workstations and Servers

Workstations and servers follow **different operational models**.

| Workstations (EUC)        | Servers (Infrastructure)     |
| ------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Frequent software updates | Controlled change cycles     |
| User productivity devices | Business-critical workloads  |
| Lower operational risk    | High operational impact      |
| Automated deployments     | Maintenance windows required |
| EUC team ownership        | Server engineering ownership |

Because of these differences, combining both workloads in the same management platform can introduce **operational complexity and governance challenges**.

---

# Slide — Key Architectural Considerations

When evaluating whether to use the existing SCCM platform or a separate instance for servers, organizations typically consider:

**Operational Risk**

• Mis-targeted deployments could affect production servers

**Ownership & Governance**

• Multiple teams sharing a single management platform can introduce operational dependency

**Infrastructure Capacity**

• Server workloads may introduce different distribution and deployment patterns

**Future Platform Strategy**

• Workstations are gradually transitioning toward **cloud-based endpoint management (Intune)**
• Maintaining platform independence allows both environments to evolve independently

These considerations often guide organizations toward **separate management environments** for servers and end-user devices.

